definition.value: A toxicity disposition that inheres in a substance that is capable of causing harm to or killing organisms when inhaled
A toxicity disposition that inheres in a substance that is capable of causing harm to or killing organisms quickly when inhaled
A toxicity disposition that inheres in a substance that is capable of causing harm to or killing organisms when inhaled multiple times
A toxicity disposition that inheres in a substance that is capable of causing harm to or killing organisms when exposed to the skin
A toxicity disposition that inheres in a substance that is capable of causing harm to or killing organisms quickly when exposed to the skin
A toxicity disposition that inheres in a substance that is capable of causing harm to or killing organisms when exposed to the skin multiple times
A toxicity disposition that inheres in a substance that is capable of damaging the genetic information within the cells of an organism, causing mutations which may lead to cancer.
A toxicity disposition that inheres in a substance that is directly involved in causing cancer.
A toxicity disposition that inheres in a substance that is capable of interfering with normal reproduction, including adverse effects on sexuality, fertility, and the developing offspring.
A toxicity disposition that inheres in a substance that is capable of causing adverse effects on a developing embryo or foetus.
Skin irritation or corrosion are localized toxic effects resulting from exposure to an agent.
Eye irritation or corrosion are localized toxic effects resulting from exposure to an agent.
Skin sensitization is induced sensitivity to an agent that in time leads to an allergic response to that agent.
A toxicity that inheres in any substances capable of interfering with normal growth, differentiation, development or behaviour as a consequence of developmental insult.
The effective concentration which produces 10% of the maximum possible response.
The effective concentration that produces 20% of the maximum possible response.
The effective concentration that produces 80% of the maximum possible response.
The effective concentration that produces 90% of the maximum possible response.
The exposure concentration that produces a 50% respiratory rate decrease

Greatest concentration or amount of a substance that causes no alteration of morphology, functional capacity, growth, development or life span of target organisms distinguishable from those observed in normal (control) organisms of the same species and strain under the same defined conditions of exposure.

Greatest concentration or amount of a substance that causes no adverse alteration of morphology, functional capacity, growth, development or life span of target organisms distinguishable from those observed in normal (control) organisms of the same species and strain under the same defined conditions of exposure.

Lowest concentration or amount of a substance, found by experiment or observation, which causes an adverse alteration of morphology, functional capacity, growth, development, or life span of a target organism distinguishable from normal (control) organisms of the same species and strain under defined conditions of exposure.

Lowest concentration or amount of a substance, found by experiment or observation, that causes any alteration in morphology, functional capacity, growth, development, or life span of target organisms distinguishable from normal (control) organisms of the same species and strain under the same defined conditions of exposure.
The highest concentration of a substance to which organisms are exposed that causes no observable adverse effect on the test organisms.
This value is used, along with other factors, to determine toxicity limits in permits.
